{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f12e9254-4054-4f2e-b47b-8576b5a92432","content":"Here's the skip attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute | Example |\n|-----------|-----------|---------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore]` | `[Ignore(\"Waiting on bug fix #123\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `Skip` property on test attribute | `[Fact(Skip = \"Waiting on bug fix #123\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"...\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore]` | `[Ignore(\"Waiting on bug fix #123\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip]` | `[Skip(\"Waiting on bug fix #123\")]` |\n\n**Key differences:**\n- xUnit has no separate attribute — `Skip` is a named parameter on `[Fact]` or `[Theory]`.\n- MSTest, NUnit, and TUnit use standalone attributes placed alongside `[TestMethod]`/`[Test]`/`[Test]` respectively.\n\nAll four frameworks will report skipped tests with your reason message in test results.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7994dc33-f184-4d4b-a2d6-ecdcd50c99ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to skip tests with a reason message in MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. This is a knowledge question about test framework attributes. I can answer this directly from my knowledge without needing to invoke any tools or skills.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer:\n\n- **MSTest**: `[Ignore(\"reason\")]`\n- **xUnit**: `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]`\n- **NUnit**: `[Ignore(\"reason\")]`\n- **TUnit**: `[Skip(\"reason\")]`\n\nThis is straightforward enough to answer directly.","outputTokens":404,"requestId":"A02D:FD35D:17B4D42:1B014B4:69FE8A4F"},"id":"c66db1e4-a094-48cd-9b31-133558665da6","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:13:58.995Z","parentId":"f166b0df-6bfa-4529-a677-ac52dbf14bfa"}
